findings.recommended_fix:
Add a dedicated subsection describing the competency assessment process for certifying and support staff, for example:

"Before issuing or extending any HTA (certifying staff) or support staff authorisation, the Technical Manager (or nominated assessor) shall perform and document a competency assessment covering:
- relevant knowledge, skills and experience for the specific aircraft type/model/variant and configuration to be maintained;
- understanding and correct application of organisation and operator procedures (e.g. component handling and identification, MEL use, technical log use, independent checks, maintenance records);
- attitude towards safety and observance of procedures.

The assessment may include oral questioning, practical observation at the workplace and/or written tests. Results are recorded in the personnel training/authorisation file and are reviewed at least every 2 years or when the scope of authorisation changes. Holding a Part‑66 licence and type rating alone is not sufficient for authorisation; the documented competency assessment must be satisfactory."

Revise the pilot/commander limited HTA section along these lines:

"Limited HTA authorisation for pilots/commanders

(a) Eligibility: The pilot shall hold a valid ATPL or CPL in accordance with Regulation (EU) No 1178/2011 (and, as applicable, Regulation (EU) 2020/723) for the aircraft type concerned.

(b) Training requirements prior to authorisation:
  - Continuing airworthiness regulation training related to maintenance (Part‑M/Part‑ML and Part‑145 basics relevant to pilot‑performed maintenance);
  - Task‑specific training for each authorised task, including use of the applicable maintenance data and practical demonstration;
  - Training on the organisation’s maintenance procedures (technical log use, defect reporting, CRS entry, use of MEL, etc.).

(c) Scope of tasks: The MOE shall list the specific minor maintenance and simple checks that may be certified by pilots, limited to tasks consistent with AMC1 145.A.30(j)(4), such as:
  - replacement of internal lights, filaments and flash tubes;
  - closing of cowlings and refitting of quick‑access inspection panels;
  - role changes (e.g. stretcher installation, dual controls, FLIR, doors, photographic equipment);
  - inspection for and removal of de‑icing/anti‑icing fluid residues, including removal/closure of easily accessible panels/cowls not requiring special tools;
  - other simple checks/replacements agreed with the competent authority.

(d) Validity: The limited authorisation is valid for a maximum of 12 months and may be renewed only after satisfactory recurrent training on the authorised tasks and procedures.

(e) All pilot limited HTA authorisations, training and assessments shall be documented in the personnel records and HTA list (5.5)."

Introduce a detailed procedure for one‑off HTA authorisations, for example:

"One‑off HTA authorisation (145.A.30(j)(5))

(a) A one‑off HTA authorisation may be issued only in unforeseen situations where the grounding of the aircraft could not reasonably have been predicted and no appropriately authorised certifying staff is available.

(b) The Compliance Monitoring Manager (CMM) is responsible for deciding on the issue of a one‑off authorisation after an individual assessment of the situation, including:
  - confirmation that the situation is unforeseen;
  - assessment that the required work does not exceed the knowledge and experience level of the proposed person;
  - verification that the person holds equivalent authorisations on other aircraft types with similar technology, construction and systems.

(c) Before issuing the authorisation, the CMM shall ensure that:
  - full technical details of the defect and required work are established and provided to the person;
  - a detailed step‑by‑step worksheet is prepared, approved and communicated to the person;
  - the organisation’s procedure for coordinating and controlling all maintenance at the location under the one‑off authorisation is applied (including communication with flight crew and operations);
  - all necessary maintenance data, tooling and test equipment are available.

(d) The holder of the one‑off authorisation shall sign off each step on the worksheet as completed. The completed tasks shall be verified by visual examination by another competent person where practicable.

(e) The one‑off authorisation is limited to the specific aircraft, defect and task(s) described in the worksheet and is valid only for that event. The authorisation and associated documentation are retained in the personnel and quality records. The NAA is notified within 7 days as currently stated."

Align the terminology ("one‑off authorisation" instead of "one‑time HTA authorisation") and clearly reference 145.A.30(j)(5).
